text: Love these inspirational uplifting movies, I buy them all. But in reality, spiritually speaking, regarding the different situations that we face, things don't progressively transpire that quickly in our lives. Sometimes it takes months to years. Watching these movies do inspire and motivate us to keep believing and keep the faith. Of course there's no mountain high enough in life that God wouldn't be able to help us reach the top.But for most of us, it takes a lot longer, it takes a lot more serious pruning, correction, molding, setbacks, to achieve what God is doing in our life and our heart, and for some it comes easier than others. I personally use to think I learned spiritual growth on the mountain, but, I was seriously wrong, it's the valleys and deserts where we get a dose of reality and gain more spiritual knowledge and grow into a new level of spiritual understanding, where we  have our eyes opened our hearts broken and humbled, it's a lifetime process called sanctification. Why did Jesus say, that in the last days, the love of many will grow cold ?, I wonder. In these undeniable godless immoral last days that we are living in today, let us not grow weary and faint. I only say this because of the tremendous struggles in my own life and heart. brother's and sister's in Christ, time is short, things will get worse in our society, and we must pray for each other. Especially for our brother's and sister's in other countries who are facing real persecution, even to death. We have it easy here in America, for now. Yes there is some resistance towards Christianity, but not like in some hostile muslim countries where they kill Christians. Our loyalty and faith will be tested here in America too, why should we be spared persecution and not our brother's and sister's in Foreign countries. Believers who actually by into the selfish teaching of the pre tribulation rapture are in for a very shocking rude awakening, I use to believe in the pre tribulation rapture myself at one time, But, no more. Let's just say for argument sake, I had my scriptural and spiritual understanding changed with some sound biblical truth. How much of the tribulation we will experience, I don't know, but we will experience it. Jesus said, whoever endures to the end, will be saved. I strongly suggest, and advice and encourage us to be ready and be prepared, earnestly and wholeheartedly seek the Lord, pray and meditate on the word of God, and keep your oil lamp FULL. spread the word, time is short.

God has established families to bring happiness to  His children, to allow us to learn correct principles in a loving  atmosphere, and to prepare us to return to Him after we die.  Although family relationships can be challenging at times, our  Heavenly Father blesses us as we strive to follow the teachings  of Jesus Christ. These teachings help us strengthen our families.   HEAVENLY FATHER REVEALS HIS GOSPEL  As part of His plan, God chooses prophets, such as Adam,  Noah, Abraham, and Moses. text: To those discouraged by recent Hillsong and Josh Harris debacle's I'd like to say the common thread in most departures from the faith is lack of "Rightly Dividing the Word of Truth". Eventually, the brain tells the feelings, "Something isn't right here." And if the brain doesn't have the tools to explain the contradictions, then the person will move on to a new source of feelings / fame / intellectual stimulation. Mid-Acts dispensationalist's like Randy White Ministries have been rightly dividing for years, saying "Acts is such a key transitional book, that without it, one could never go from Luke to Romans without tossing the whole thing in the trash.."  Something happened before AD70 to slowly transition the Bible message from a Petristic Gospel of Christ (a rejected Kingdom offer made to the Jews), to a simplistic Pauline Gospel by Faith alone to everyone of all nations.. without distinction. Your task, should you choose to accept it, is to re-read Acts to Romans 11, and determine if God really has put the nation of Israel "on the shelf" until the "times of the Gentiles be fulfilled" (blatant clue: yes there was a dispensation change).

text: Obviously, the target demographic here is evangelical Christians, who sometimes need external validation and reassurance just like everyone else . As for everyone else, they're unlikely to find the message compelling and some with more sensitive digestion may find the ham-fisted proselytizing gag-inducing. The script is clunky, predictable and as nuanced as an invitation in your mailbox to some local church service. The acting ranges from average for this sort of thing to cringe-worthy, and the cinematography is uninteresting. Evangelicals may find the film as inspiring as Jesus' feeding of the five thousand. Anyone else is likely to regard it as rancid fish and moldy bread.

text: Ok... as a person from Columbus, Georgia (the place this movie was filmed), I'm going to talk about how wack this movie's setting is. First of all the school is called Brookshire High School which is a direct copy of Brookstone High School, an actual school in Columbus, Georgia. They even have the same logo and mascot, the cougars.  Brookstone is the most expensive private school in the city, and they are also the only ones that have mandatory drug testing of all students from grades 8-12. This is because they have had issues with their students and drugs for a very long time. The most ironic part of all this is that Brookshire is portrayed as a struggling school with pay cuts and the obvious shortage of faculty members, but in actuality, Brookstone has a reputation of having some of the richest students, an enormous campus, and of course rich parents. The worst part of all this is that Brookstone school's rival is a CATHOLIC school called St. Anne-Pacelli Catholic School. Pacelli has a tiny campus, a lack of proper funding and faculty, and very poor classroom conditions. Only in recent years have they recently been given money for proper AP classes and better conditions. It's so weird to a Columbus, GA resident (and alum of Pacelli high school), to see the narrative be so twisted. Wouldn't it make sense for a financially struggling catholic school be the setting for a movie like this?
